# Native Engine Port Standards (Unity / Unreal)

Use these if/when this game is ported to a native engine. Auto-applies when
C#/C++/Unreal source files are present.

## Architecture
- Respect engine lifecycle: init/caching in `Awake`/`Start` (Unity) or
  `BeginPlay` (Unreal); per-frame work in `Update`, physics in `FixedUpdate`.
- Unreal: keep logic decoupled between C++ and Blueprints; expose tunables.

## Performance first
- NEVER call `GameObject.Find`, `GetComponent`, or string/tag lookups inside
  update loops. Cache all references in `Awake`/`Start`/`BeginPlay`.
```csharp
// BAD
void Update() { GetComponent<Rigidbody>().AddForce(dir); }
// GOOD
Rigidbody _rb;
void Awake() { _rb = GetComponent<Rigidbody>(); }
void Update() { _rb.AddForce(dir); }
```

## Component-driven
- Favor composition over inheritance. Scripts are modular, reusable,
  single-purpose components.

## Input & events
- Use the modern Input System, and event-driven architecture (C# events,
  UnityEvents, or Unreal delegates) instead of constant state polling.

## Memory management
- Avoid `Instantiate`/`Spawn` in runtime loops. Use object pooling for
  projectiles, particles, and other recurring items.

## Code quality
- Proper access modifiers: `private [SerializeField]`, `public`, `protected`.
- Comment complex math or state logic clearly and concisely.
